<HEADLINE>
<P>
IS THIS POLITICAL ACT TOO TOUGH TO FOLLOW? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN SCHRAM, Martin Schram is a syndicated columnist in Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the election of 1990, Democrats can take heart in the fact that the public 
is considerably smarter than the politicians and strategists who try to 
game-plan each election campaign. Voters have put their faith in our 
Constitution's separation of powers and take pride in electing Democratic 
senators and representatives who will check and balance their chosen Republican 
President. 
</P>
<P>
But Democrats may find much less to cheer about after that. For the 
presidential election of 1992 may be when the true political impact of the 
current Mideast crisis is seen. 
</P>
<P>
The super summit events that dominated our screens this weekend are certainly 
causing some second thoughts within the most private councils of the Mario 
Cuomos and Sam Nunns and Albert Gores and Richard Gephardts and Charles Robbs 
and all other Democrats who may have entertained the notion of running for 
President. 
</P>
<P>
These are Democrats who can all say with confidence that they could lead where 
President Bush has faltered in shaping new policies on issues from the federal 
budget and economy to global warming. But running for President is a very 
personal thing. And so now all prospective Democratic candidates must be 
looking at their TV screens and asking themselves this personal, soul-searching 
question: 
</P>
<P>
Am I confident that I could have responded as swiftly and skillfully -- 
militarily and diplomatically -- as did Bush if the Iraqi crisis happened on my 
presidential watch? 
</P>
<P>
Unless their private answer is a resounding yes, it will be hard for any of 
them to mount a campaign against Bush in 1992, let alone beat him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, KAL 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
