<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
YELLOW RIBBON CIVIL WAR REMINDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BILOXI, Miss. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Entertainer Tony Orlando feels something special for those yellow ribbons, the 
ubiquitous symbol of hope for loved ones held captive. 
</P>
<P>
The singer known for "Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Old Oak Tree" said in a 
telephone interview last week that he discovered the song's deep emotional 
effect shortly after it was released. 
</P>
<P>
It was in 1973, and the group Dawn, featuring Orlando as lead singer, was the 
opening act at a Bob Hope show at the Cotton Bowl in Dallas. About 400 or 500 
former prisoners of war were seated in front of the stage. 
</P>
<P>
The song is based on a Civil War story about the homecoming of a Union soldier 
from a Confederate prison. In the song, the man is welcomed by yellow ribbons 
as he comes home from a stint in prison. The message moved the former POWs. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm on stage and I'm singing this song and all of a sudden it was the most 
spine-chilling moment," he said. "Up they got, off their chairs, and they're 
coming toward the stage and they come on stage and they begin to sing the 
song." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
